# College of the Holy Cross  

[[File:Holy_Cross_Crusaders_logo.svg|thumb|200px|The College of the Holy Cross shield, used as the primary athletic logo]]  

The **College of the Holy Cross** is a private Jesuit liberal arts college in Worcester, Massachusetts, United States. [[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College_of_the_Holy_Cross)] It was founded in 1843 by Bishop **Benedict Joseph Fenwick** and **Thomas F. Mulledy** under the auspices of the Society of Jesus. [[2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benedict_Joseph_Fenwick)] It holds the distinction of being the first Catholic college in New England and one of the oldest Catholic institutions of higher education in the United States. [[3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_higher_education)]  

The college operates as a four‑year residential undergraduate institution with approximately 3,219 students. [[4](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College_of_the_Holy_Cross)] Students may select from 64 academic programs, encompassing interdisciplinary and self‑designed majors within the liberal arts spectrum. [[5](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberal_arts_colleges_in_the_United_States)] The campus, spanning 174 acres (70 hectares), sits on a hill overlooking the Blackstone River and the city of Worcester. [[6](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worcester,_Massachusetts)] It boasts one of the largest financial endowments among liberal arts colleges in the United States, valued at $1.109 billion in 2024. [[7](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_endowment)]  

The athletic teams are nicknamed the **Crusaders** and compete in NCAA Division I as members of the Patriot League, Atlantic Hockey America, Hockey East, and EARC for rowing. [[8](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patriot_League)] The college’s official colors are purple and white. [[9](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/School_colors)]  

