## History  

=== Founding ===  

The College of the Holy Cross was established by **Benedict Joseph Fenwick**, the second Bishop of Boston, as the first Catholic institution of higher learning in New England. [[10](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benedict_Joseph_Fenwick)] The initiative arose after Fenwick’s attempts to create a Catholic college in Boston were thwarted by the city’s Protestant civic leadership. [[11](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston)] The surge of Irish Catholic immigrants after 1830 heightened the need for a Jesuit‑run educational facility. [[12](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Americans)]  

Fenwick initially considered a site in **Benedicta, Maine**, but ultimately selected Worcester, Massachusetts, for greater autonomy. [[13](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worcester,_Massachusetts)] In August 1843 the Society of Jesus approved the proposal, sending **Thomas F. Mulledy** to assess the location. [[14](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_F._Mulledy)] Mulledy’s favorable report secured the Society’s endorsement, and the college was chartered on March 24, 1865, after earlier legislative rejections rooted in anti‑Catholic sentiment. [[15](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Catholicism)]  

The cornerstone of **Fenwick Hall**, the inaugural building, was laid on June 21, 1843. [[16](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fenwick_Hall)] The institution opened its doors in October 1843 with Jesuit president **Thomas F. Mulledy** and six students ranging in age from nine to nineteen. [[17](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_F._Mulledy)] Within three years enrollment grew to 100 students, initially focusing on elementary and secondary education before evolving into a full‑scale liberal arts college. [[18](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College_of_the_Holy_Cross)]  

=== Early Development ===  

The first graduating class in 1849 was led by valedictorian **James Augustine Healy**, a mixed‑race son of an Irish plantation owner and an enslaved woman. [[19](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Augustine_Healy)] Though he identified as white Irish Catholic at the time, Healy is now recognized as the first African‑American bishop in the United States. [[20](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Augustine_Healy)] Fenwick Hall was destroyed by fire in 1852; the college rebuilt and reopened in 1853. [[21](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fire)]  

The college’s original charter was denied multiple times by the Massachusetts legislature due largely to anti‑Catholic prejudice during the Irish famine migration. [[22](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charter_of_the_College_of_the_Holy_Cross)] It was not until March 24, 1865, that Governor **John Albion Andrew** granted the charter. [[23](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Albion_Andrew)]  

=== 20th‑Century Milestones ===  

During **World War II**, Holy Cross participated in the V‑12 Navy College Training Program, a national effort to prepare students for naval commissions. [[24](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V-12_Navy_College_Training_Program)] In 1998 the college launched the eight‑year capital campaign “**Lift High the Cross**,” raising $216.3 million by fiscal 2006, surpassing its original $175 million goal. [[25](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lift_High_the_Cross)] The campaign enabled the creation of twelve new faculty positions and over 75 endowed scholarships, expanding the endowment to over $544 million. [[26](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endowment)]  

In 2000 **Michael C. McFarland** became president, succeeded in 2011 by **Philip L. Boroughs**, and in 2021 by **Vincent D. Rougeau**, the first lay and first Black president in the college’s history. [[27](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vincent_Rougeau)]  

A 2018 proposal to retire the “Knight” mascot imagery was considered, but the administration ultimately retained the Crusader nickname while phasing out the traditional knight iconography. [[28](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holy_Cross_Crusaders)]  

In 2019 the college discontinued its need‑blind admissions policy, shifting toward a need‑aware model. [[29](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Need-blind_admissions)]  

