## Campus  

The 174‑acre (70‑hectare) suburban campus is situated on a hill overlooking Worcester and the Blackstone River, an area colloquially known as “**The Hill**.” [[30](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hill_(Holy_Cross))] The design reflects a blend of Classical Revival, Gothic, and Second Empire architectural styles, with many buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places. [[31](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places)]  

Key structures include:  

* **Fenwick Hall** – the flagship building, named for the founding bishop. [[32](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fenwick_Hall)]  
* **O’Kane Hall** – connected to Fenwick, housing admissions offices and the Brooks Concert Hall. [[33](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O%27Kane_Hall)]  
* **Dinand Library** – the main library, expanded in 1978 to include memorial wings for the Hiatt family and Holocaust victims. [[34](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinand_Library)]  
* **Smith Hall** – home to the Anthony S. Fauci Integrated Science Complex, housing O’Neil, Swords, and Haberlin Halls. [[35](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Fauci)]  
* **Prior Performing Arts Center** – a $110 million, 84,000‑square‑foot facility opened in 2022, designed by Diller Scofidio + Renfro, featuring the Cantor Art Gallery. [[36](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_Performing_Arts_Center)]  
* **Worcester Art Museum Library** – a satellite collection supporting visual‑arts research. [[37](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worcester_Art_Museum)]  

The campus also includes six non‑campus properties, an arboretum, and numerous historic statues, including works by Enzo Plazzotta, Georg Klobe, and Welrick. [[38](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enzo_Plazzotta)]  

