## Academic Programs  

Holy Cross offers 64 majors across the liberal arts disciplines, emphasizing interdisciplinary study and self‑designed concentrations. [[39](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberal_arts_education)] Core curriculum requirements include at least one course each in arts, literature, religion, philosophy, history, and cross‑cultural studies, plus two courses each in language studies, social science, and natural/mathematical sciences. [[40](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Core_curriculum)]  

The college maintains a faculty of roughly 350 scholars who teach an undergraduate enrollment of about 3,142 students. [[41](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undergraduate_education)] Popular majors, as of the 2021 graduating class, include Economics, Psychology, Political Science & Government, English Language and Literature, Biology, and History. [[42](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academic_statistics)]  

### Notable Departments  

* **Political Science** – renowned for producing policy analysts and public‑service leaders. [[43](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_science)]  
* **Economics** – consistently ranked among the top liberal‑arts economics programs. [[44](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics)]  
* **Classics** – one of the largest classics departments in the nation. [[45](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classics)]  
* **Religious Studies** – reflects the Jesuit mission of theological inquiry. [[46](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religious_studies)]  

