## Student Life  

### Residential Life  

All freshmen reside on campus, and upperclassmen may choose from a variety of residence halls, including **Easy Street**, **Alumni**, **Carlin**, **Loyola**, as well as senior apartments in **Williams Hall**, **Figge Hall**, and townhouses. [[59](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residential_life_(college))] Williams and Figge Halls feature apartment‑style units with kitchens, separate bathrooms, and living rooms. [[60](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Williams_Hall_(College_of_the_Holy_Cross))]  

### Student Organizations  

Holy Cross hosts a vibrant array of student groups, ranging from service organizations such as **SPUD** (Student Programs for Urban Development) to media outlets like **The Spire** (weekly newspaper), **The Fenwick Review** (conservative journal), and **The Advocate** (liberal journal). [[61](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student_organizations)] The college operates a non‑commercial FM radio station, **WCHC‑FM 88.1**, and fields a student‑run law journal, **The Holy Cross Journal of Law & Public Policy**. [[62](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WCHC_(FM))]  

Athletics and spirit are supported by the **Holy Cross Goodtime Marching Band**, the cheer squad, and the **Knights of Columbus** council, the third‑oldest college council in the order. [[63](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knights_of_Columbus)]  

### Social Justice & Service  

The college’s commitment to social justice is evident through participation in the **Jesuit Volunteer Corps**, where Holy Cross graduates rank highest among Jesuit institutions for service placements. [[64](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesuit_Volunteer_Corps)] Programs such as **Arrupe Immersion**, **Pax Christi**, and **Appalachia Service Project** provide experiential learning opportunities. [[65](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_justice)]  

